---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../../components/CodeBlock.astro';
import Callout from '../../components/Callout.astro';
import StepList from '../../components/StepList.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="Web dev setup" description="How the methodology works and everything you need to install for Web Development.">
  <h1 class="mb-6">Getting Started with Web Dev</h1>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">How the methodology works, then every tool you need — installed and verified.</p>

  <!-- How This Works -->
  <h2 class="mb-6 mt-12">How this works</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">You direct AI to build real software. You'll learn to read, inspect, and challenge the code AI produces, without writing it yourself.</p>

  <h3 class="mb-4">The Roles</h3>
  <div class="grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-3 mb-8">
    <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6 text-center">
      <div class="w-14 h-14 rounded-full bg-primary-bg text-primary font-bold text-2xl flex items-center justify-center mx-auto mb-3">D</div>
      <h4 class="text-base font-semibold mb-2">You — the Director</h4>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">Decide what gets built, review the work, verify it's correct, sign off on every change.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6 text-center">
      <div class="w-14 h-14 rounded-full bg-primary-bg text-primary font-bold text-2xl flex items-center justify-center mx-auto mb-3">C</div>
      <h4 class="text-base font-semibold mb-2">Claude Code — AI Developer</h4>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">Writes code, creates files, runs tests, opens pull requests. Fast and capable, but makes mistakes.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6 text-center">
      <div class="w-14 h-14 rounded-full bg-primary-bg text-primary font-bold text-2xl flex items-center justify-center mx-auto mb-3">G</div>
      <h4 class="text-base font-semibold mb-2">Gemini — AI Reviewer</h4>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">Independently reviews every pull request for security issues and best practices.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3 class="mb-4">The Loop</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Every project follows the same cycle:</p>
  <StepList steps={[
    { title: "Plan", content: "Give AI a brief and a template. Review the PRD it produces. Catch scope creep and vague requirements." },
    { title: "Architect", content: "AI produces the technical design: schema, API contracts, ticket backlog. You review for over-engineering." },
    { title: "Build (ticket by ticket)", content: "Claude creates a branch, implements, commits, opens a PR. Both AIs review. You verify and decide: merge or fix." },
    { title: "Deploy", content: "Ship to a staging URL. Verify it works on a real server, not just on your laptop." },
    { title: "Client Feedback", content: "Show the client. Collect feedback. Create small tickets (CF-1, CF-2…), fix them with the same loop, then get sign-off." },
    { title: "Production", content: "Point a custom domain. Final verification. The client's site is live." },
    { title: "Reflect", content: "What went well? What did AI get wrong? What would you do differently? Lessons feed into the next project." },
  ]} />

  <h3 class="mb-4 mt-8">What you actually do</h3>
  <div class="space-y-4 mb-8">
    <div class="border-l-4 border-l-primary bg-primary-bg p-4 rounded-r-lg">
      <p class="font-semibold text-sm mb-1">Planning</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">Catch what AI added that wasn't asked for, what it described vaguely, and what it missed entirely.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="border-l-4 border-l-primary bg-primary-bg p-4 rounded-r-lg">
      <p class="font-semibold text-sm mb-1">Reviewing</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">Read both AI reviews. Develop judgment about real issues vs false positives.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="border-l-4 border-l-primary bg-primary-bg p-4 rounded-r-lg">
      <p class="font-semibold text-sm mb-1">Verifying</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">Open the product and test it like a real user. Try to break it.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="border-l-4 border-l-primary bg-primary-bg p-4 rounded-r-lg">
      <p class="font-semibold text-sm mb-1">Communicating</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">Explain technical decisions clearly. You directed the work — you understand what was built.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Setup -->
  <h2 class="mb-6 mt-16 pt-8 border-t border-border">Setup</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">Your operating system, the terminal, six tools, and two accounts. About 30–60 minutes.</p>

  <!-- The Terminal -->
  <h3 class="mb-4">The terminal</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Everything in this course happens in a terminal — a text-based interface where you type commands instead of clicking buttons. If you've never used one, that's fine. Here's what you need to know:</p>

  <div class="space-y-3 mb-6">
    <div class="flex gap-3 items-start">
      <span class="text-primary font-bold mt-0.5">$</span>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary"><strong class="text-text">The dollar sign is a prompt.</strong> When you see <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">$ git --version</code>, you type <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">git --version</code> and press Enter. Don't type the $.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="flex gap-3 items-start">
      <span class="text-primary font-bold mt-0.5">→</span>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary"><strong class="text-text">Commands run in a directory.</strong> Your terminal is always "in" a folder. Use <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">pwd</code> to see where you are, <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">cd foldername</code> to move into a folder, and <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">ls</code> to list what's inside.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="flex gap-3 items-start">
      <span class="text-primary font-bold mt-0.5">↑</span>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary"><strong class="text-text">Press ↑ to repeat.</strong> The up arrow cycles through previous commands. You'll use this constantly.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="flex gap-3 items-start">
      <span class="text-primary font-bold mt-0.5">⌃</span>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary"><strong class="text-text">Ctrl+C stops things.</strong> If a command is running and you want to stop it (like a dev server), press Ctrl+C.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4"><strong>How to open it:</strong> On Mac, open <strong>Terminal</strong> (Applications → Utilities). On Linux, open your terminal emulator. On Windows with WSL, open <strong>Ubuntu</strong> from the Start menu.</p>

  <details class="mb-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary>Want a fuller introduction?</summary>
    <div class="p-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">MDN has a good beginner guide: <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Learn_web_development/Getting_started/Environment_setup/Command_line">Command line crash course</a>. Read the first few sections — you don't need to memorise everything. You'll pick up the rest as you go.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <!-- Choose your platform -->
  <h3 class="mb-4">Choose your platform</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">The commands in this course are written for Mac and Linux. If you're on Windows, you have two good options.</p>

  <div class="grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-3 mb-8">
    <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
      <h4 class="text-base font-semibold mb-2">Mac</h4>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">Works out of the box. Open Terminal (in Applications → Utilities) and you're ready. All commands in this guide work as-is.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
      <h4 class="text-base font-semibold mb-2">Linux</h4>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">The best development experience. If you have a Windows machine, consider dual-booting Ubuntu — you'll have a native Linux environment with no compatibility issues. All commands work as-is.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
      <h4 class="text-base font-semibold mb-2">Windows + WSL</h4>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">If you'd rather not dual-boot, install WSL (Windows Subsystem for Linux). It gives you a real Linux terminal inside Windows. All commands work as-is inside WSL.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Recommended for Windows users:</strong> Install WSL before anything else. It avoids path issues, permission headaches, and incompatible line endings that trip people up later. Once WSL is set up, follow the Linux instructions for everything below.</p>
  </Callout>

  <details class="mt-4 mb-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary>How to install WSL</summary>
    <div class="p-4 space-y-3">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">Open PowerShell as Administrator and run:</p>
      <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ wsl --install`}</CodeBlock>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">This installs WSL 2 with Ubuntu. Restart your computer when prompted.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">After restart, Ubuntu will open and ask you to create a username and password. These are for Linux only — they don't need to match your Windows credentials.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">From now on, open <strong>Ubuntu</strong> from your Start menu (not PowerShell or Command Prompt) for all development work. VS Code integrates with WSL automatically — when you run <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">code .</code> from WSL, it opens with full Linux support.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <!-- 1. VS Code -->
  <h3 class="mb-4">1. VS Code</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4"><strong class="text-text">What it is:</strong> A free code editor. You won't write code in it — you'll read what Claude creates and verify it.</p>

  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2"><strong>Mac:</strong> Download from <a href="https://code.visualstudio.com">code.visualstudio.com</a> and drag to Applications.</p>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2"><strong>Linux / WSL:</strong></p>
  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ sudo apt update
$ sudo apt install code`}</CodeBlock>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2">Or download the .deb package from <a href="https://code.visualstudio.com">code.visualstudio.com</a> and install with <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">sudo dpkg -i code_*.deb</code>.</p>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4"><strong>Windows (without WSL):</strong> Download from <a href="https://code.visualstudio.com">code.visualstudio.com</a> and run the installer.</p>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>WSL users:</strong> Install VS Code on Windows (not inside WSL). Then install the <strong>WSL extension</strong> in VS Code. When you run <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">code .</code> from your WSL terminal, VS Code opens with full Linux filesystem access.</p>
  </Callout>

  <h4 class="mb-2 mt-4">Verify</h4>
  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ code --version`}</CodeBlock>

  <details class="mb-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary>Troubleshooting: "command not found: code"</summary>
    <div class="p-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary"><strong>Mac:</strong> Open VS Code → Cmd+Shift+P → type "Shell Command" → click "Install 'code' command in PATH."</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-2"><strong>Linux:</strong> If you installed via .deb, the command should be available. Try restarting your terminal.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <!-- 2. Git -->
  <h3 class="mb-4">2. Git</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4"><strong class="text-text">What it is:</strong> Version control. Every change to every file is tracked. You can always go back.</p>

  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2"><strong>Mac:</strong></p>
  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ git --version`}</CodeBlock>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4">If Git isn't installed, macOS will prompt you to install Command Line Tools — click Install and wait.</p>

  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2"><strong>Linux / WSL:</strong></p>
  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ sudo apt update && sudo apt install git -y`}</CodeBlock>

  <h4 class="mb-2 mt-4">Configure (all platforms)</h4>
  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ git config --global user.name "Your Name"
$ git config --global user.email "your.email@example.com"`}</CodeBlock>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2">Use the same email you'll use for your GitHub account.</p>

  <h4 class="mb-2 mt-4">Verify</h4>
  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ git --version`}</CodeBlock>

  <!-- 3. GitHub -->
  <h3 class="mb-4 mt-8">3. GitHub Account & CLI</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4"><strong class="text-text">What it is:</strong> GitHub stores your code online. The CLI lets you create repos, open PRs, and manage boards from the terminal.</p>

  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4"><strong>Create an account:</strong> Go to <a href="https://github.com">github.com</a> and sign up (free).</p>

  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2"><strong>Install the CLI — Mac:</strong></p>
  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ brew install gh`}</CodeBlock>
  <details class="mb-4 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary>Don't have Homebrew?</summary>
    <div class="p-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">Homebrew is a package manager for Mac. Install it first:</p>
      <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ /bin/bash -c "$(curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Homebrew/install/HEAD/install.sh)"`}</CodeBlock>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-2">Follow the instructions it prints at the end — you may need to add Homebrew to your PATH.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2"><strong>Linux / WSL:</strong></p>
  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ sudo apt install gh -y`}</CodeBlock>

  <h4 class="mb-2 mt-4">Log in</h4>
  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ gh auth login`}</CodeBlock>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2">Choose: GitHub.com → HTTPS → Login with a web browser. It will give you a code to enter at github.com/login/device.</p>

  <h4 class="mb-2 mt-4">Verify</h4>
  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ gh auth status`}</CodeBlock>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2">Should show "Logged in to github.com."</p>

  <details class="mb-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary>Troubleshooting: "gh auth login" hangs or fails</summary>
    <div class="p-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">Try: <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">gh auth login --web</code> to force browser-based auth. If you're in WSL, make sure your default browser is configured — or copy the URL manually.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <!-- 4. Node.js -->
  <h3 class="mb-4">4. Node.js</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4"><strong class="text-text">What it is:</strong> The JavaScript runtime. The project tooling, build system, and web stack all depend on it.</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4"><strong class="text-text">Target version:</strong> Node.js 20 LTS — the current Long Term Support release with the widest compatibility.</p>

  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2"><strong>Mac:</strong></p>
  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ brew install node@20`}</CodeBlock>

  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2"><strong>Linux / WSL:</strong></p>
  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ curl -fsSL https://deb.nodesource.com/setup_20.x | sudo -E bash -
$ sudo apt install nodejs -y`}</CodeBlock>

  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4"><strong>Any platform:</strong> Or download the installer from <a href="https://nodejs.org">nodejs.org</a> — choose the <strong>LTS</strong> version.</p>

  <h4 class="mb-2">Verify</h4>
  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ node --version
$ npm --version`}</CodeBlock>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2">Node should show v20.x.x. npm comes bundled with Node.</p>

  <details class="mb-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary>Troubleshooting: wrong Node version</summary>
    <div class="p-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">If you have an older version, uninstall it and reinstall from <a href="https://nodejs.org">nodejs.org</a>. If you use nvm, run: <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">nvm install 20 && nvm use 20</code>.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <!-- 5. Claude Code -->
  <h3 class="mb-4">5. Claude Code</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4"><strong class="text-text">What it is:</strong> Your AI developer. You direct it from the terminal — it writes code, creates files, runs tests, and opens pull requests.</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4"><strong class="text-text">You need:</strong> A Claude Pro ($20/month) or Max subscription from <a href="https://claude.ai">claude.ai</a>. This gives you access to Claude Code. Note: this is a subscription to claude.ai, not API credits — they're different products.</p>

  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code`}</CodeBlock>

  <h4 class="mb-2 mt-4">Verify</h4>
  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ claude --version`}</CodeBlock>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2">When you run <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">claude</code> for the first time, it will open your browser to authenticate.</p>

  <details class="mb-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary>Troubleshooting: permission errors on Mac/Linux</summary>
    <div class="p-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">Run with sudo: <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">sudo npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code</code></p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-2">Or fix npm permissions permanently: <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">mkdir ~/.npm-global && npm config set prefix '~/.npm-global'</code> then add <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">export PATH=~/.npm-global/bin:$PATH</code> to your ~/.bashrc or ~/.zshrc.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <!-- 6. Docker -->
  <h3 class="mb-4">6. Docker</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4"><strong class="text-text">What it is:</strong> Runs applications in isolated containers. From Project 2 onwards, your database, backend, and frontend all run in Docker.</p>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm">You don't need Docker for Project 1. Install it now so it's ready for Project 2.</p>
  </Callout>

  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2 mt-4"><strong>Mac:</strong></p>
  <StepList steps={[
    { title: "Download Docker Desktop from docker.com/products/docker-desktop" },
    { title: "Install (drag to Applications)" },
    { title: "Open Docker Desktop — it runs in the background" },
  ]} />

  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2"><strong>Linux:</strong></p>
  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ sudo apt update
$ sudo apt install docker.io docker-compose-v2 -y
$ sudo usermod -aG docker $USER`}</CodeBlock>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4">Log out and back in for the group change to take effect.</p>

  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2"><strong>WSL:</strong> Install Docker Desktop on Windows (not inside WSL). In Docker Desktop settings, enable <strong>"Use the WSL 2 based engine"</strong> and under Resources → WSL Integration, enable your Ubuntu distribution. Docker commands will then work from your WSL terminal.</p>

  <h4 class="mb-2 mt-4">Verify</h4>
  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ docker --version
$ docker compose version`}</CodeBlock>

  <details class="mb-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary>Troubleshooting: "docker: command not found"</summary>
    <div class="p-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary"><strong>Mac/Windows:</strong> Docker Desktop must be running. Look for the whale icon in your system tray.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-2"><strong>Linux:</strong> If you just added yourself to the docker group, you need to log out and back in (or run <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">newgrp docker</code>).</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-2"><strong>WSL:</strong> Make sure Docker Desktop is running on Windows and WSL integration is enabled in settings.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <!-- Accounts -->
  <h3 class="mb-4">Accounts you'll need later</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Create these now so they're ready when the projects need them.</p>

  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
    <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr class="bg-bg-muted">
          <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">Account</th>
          <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">Free?</th>
          <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">When</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Netlify</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Project 1</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border bg-bg-subtle">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Gemini API key</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Yes</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Project 2</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2"><strong>Netlify:</strong> Sign up at <a href="https://netlify.com">netlify.com</a> with your GitHub account. You'll connect it to your project repo in Project 1.</p>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-6"><strong>Gemini API key:</strong> Go to <a href="https://aistudio.google.com/apikey">aistudio.google.com/apikey</a>, sign in with Google, click "Create API Key", and save it somewhere safe. You'll add it to GitHub Secrets in Project 2.</p>

  <!-- Verify everything -->
  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-12">Verify everything</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Run all of these. Every one should succeed:</p>
  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ code --version
$ git --version
$ gh auth status
$ node --version
$ npm --version
$ claude --version
$ docker --version
$ docker compose version`}</CodeBlock>

  <!-- Ready -->
  <div class="mt-12 p-6 bg-primary-bg rounded-lg border border-primary/20 text-center">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-2">You're ready</h2>
    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">All tools installed. Time to build your first project.</p>
    <a
      href="/web-dev/projects/1"
      class="inline-block bg-primary hover:bg-primary-dark text-white font-semibold py-3 px-6 rounded-md transition-colors min-h-[44px]"
    >
      Start Project 1: The Static Site
    </a>
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
